Our hypothesis is that the sentiment expressed in the tweets about the airlines and their on-time performance, as indicated by the delay information in the Delay_Airlines.csv dataset, are the main drivers of their popularity.

Methodology:

  • Data Cleaning: Next, we will perform data cleaning on both datasets to remove any missing or inconsistent values.
  • Data Aggregation: We will aggregate the data by grouping it by airline and time to get a better understanding of the popularity of each airline over time.
  • Data Visualization: We will use data visualization techniques, such as bar charts, heat maps, and scatter plots, to represent the data and find any patterns or relationships between variables.
  • Statistical analysis: Finally, we will perform statistical analysis, such as hypothesis testing and regression analysis, to determine if there is a significant relationship between the sentiment expressed in the tweets and the on-time performance of the airlines.

Assumptions:

  • The tweets in the Tweets.csv dataset are a representative sample of the sentiment towards each airline.
  • The sentiment expressed in the tweets is a reliable indicator of the overall popularity of each airline.
  • The on-time performance information in the Delay_Airlines.csv dataset is a reliable indicator of the performance of each airline.

df_tweets = pd.read_csv('tweets.csv')  
df_airlines = pd.read_csv("delay_airlines.csv")
# Filter out the rows that don't contain the UNIQUE_CARRIER codes in the dictionary
df_airlines = df_airlines[df_airlines['CARRIER'].isin(["AA", "DL", "VX", "UA", "US", "WN"])]
airlines_lookup = {'AA': "American", 
                   'AS': "Alaska Airlines", 
                   'B6': "JetBlue", 
                   'DL': "Delta", 
                   'EV': "ExpressJet", 
                   'F9': "Frontier", 
                   'HA': "Hawaiian", 
                   'MQ': "Envoy Air", 
                   'NK': "Spirit", 
                   'OO': "SkyWest", 
                   'UA': "United",
                   'US': "US Airways", 
                   'VX': "Virgin America", 
                   'WN': "Southwest"}

df_airlines['UNIQUE_CARRIER'] = df_airlines['UNIQUE_CARRIER'].map(airlines_lookup)

airlines_lookup = {'Virgin America': "VX", 
                   'United': "UA", 
                   'Southwest': "WN", 
                   'Delta': "DL", 
                   'US Airways': "US",
                   'American': "AA"}

def lookup_value(x):
    return airlines_lookup.get(x, "empty")

def convert_t(x):
    return x[0:10]

df_tweets["UNIQUE_CARRIER"] = df_tweets["airline"].apply(lookup_value)
df_tweets["FL_DATE"] = df_tweets["tweet_created"].apply(convert_t)

plt.ylabel('Number of tweets')
plt.title('Popularity of airlines based on tweet count')

def show_wordcloud(data, title = None):
    wordcloud = WordCloud(
        background_color='white',
        max_words=200,
        max_font_size=40, 
        scale=3,
        random_state=1 
    ).generate(str(data))

    fig = plt.figure(1, figsize=(12, 12))
    plt.axis('off')
    if title: 
        fig.suptitle(title, fontsize=20)
        fig.subplots_adjust(top=2.3)

    plt.imshow(wordcloud)
    plt.show()

show_wordcloud(df_tweets["text"], title = "Common Words from Tweets")

# Group the data by airline and count the number of tweets for each airline
tweets_by_airline = df_tweets.groupby("airline")["tweet_id"].count().reset_index(name="num_tweets")


# Group the data by carrier and count the number of flights for each carrier
flights_by_carrier = df_airlines.groupby("CARRIER")["UNIQUE_CARRIER"].count().reset_index(name="num_flights")

# Create a dictionary to map the UNIQUE_CARRIER code to the airline name
carrier_map = {
    "AA": "American",
    "DL": "Delta",
    "VX": "Virgin America",
    "UA": "United",
    "US": "US Airways",
    "WN": "Southwest"
}

# Convert the UNIQUE_CARRIER code to the airline name using the dictionary
flights_by_carrier["airline"] = flights_by_carrier["CARRIER"].map(carrier_map)

# Merge the two datasets on the airline column
result = pd.merge(tweets_by_airline, flights_by_carrier, on="airline")

# Display the result
print(result[["airline", "num_tweets", "num_flights"]])

df_negative = df_tweets[df_tweets['airline_sentiment'] == 'negative']

grouped = df_negative.groupby('airline').count()

# Get the airline with the most negative tweets
most_hated_airline = grouped.idxmax()[0]

# Filter the dataframe to only include negative tweets for the most hated airline
df_most_hated = df_negative[df_negative['airline'] == most_hated_airline]

# Group the negative tweets by reason and get the count for each reason

# Get the most common reason for negative tweets
most_common_reason = grouped_reasons.idxmax()[0]

# Print the result
print(f"The most hated airline is {most_hated_airline} and the most common reason for negative tweets is {most_common_reason}")

In [53]:
# Group the tweets by airline and count the number of positive and negative tweets
grouped = df_tweets.groupby(['airline', 'airline_sentiment']).count()

# Reset the index and pivot the dataframe to have airline_sentiment as columns
grouped = grouped.reset_index().pivot(index='airline', columns='airline_sentiment', values='tweet_id')

# Fill any missing values with 0
grouped.fillna(0, inplace=True)

# Calculate the total number of positive and negative tweets for each airline
grouped['total_positive'] = grouped['positive']
grouped['total_negative'] = grouped['negative']

# Calculate the overall sentiment by dividing the number of positive tweets by the total number of tweets
grouped['overall_sentiment'] = grouped['total_positive'] / (grouped['total_positive'] + grouped['total_negative'])

# Find the airline with the highest overall sentiment
most_loved_airline = grouped.sort_values(by='overall_sentiment', ascending=False).iloc[0].name
print(f'The most loved airline is: {most_loved_airline}')

The most loved airline is: Virgin America
